<meta name="citation_author" content="Nigam H. Shah" /><meta name="citation_author_institution" content="Stanford Health Care, Palo Alto, California" /><meta name="citation_author_institution" content="Department of Medicine, School of Medicine, Stanford University, Stanford, California" /><meta name="citation_author_institution" content="Clinical Excellence Research Center, School of Medicine, Stanford University, Stanford, California" /><meta name="citation_author" content="David Entwistle" /><meta name="citation_author_institution" content="Stanford Health Care, Palo Alto, California" /><meta name="citation_author" content="Michael A. Pfeffer" /><meta name="citation_author_institution" content="Stanford Health Care, Palo Alto, California" /><meta name="citation_author_institution" content="Department of Medicine, School of Medicine, Stanford University, Stanford, California" /><meta name="citation_title" content="Creation and Adoption of Large Language Models in Medicine" /><meta name="citation_firstpage" content="866" /><meta name="citation_lastpage" content="869" /><meta name="citation_doi" content="10.1001/jama.2023.14217" /><meta name="citation_keyword" content="large language models" /><meta name="citation_keyword" content="professional supervision" /><meta name="citation_keyword" content="verification" /><meta name="citation_abstract" content="&lt;h3&gt;Importance&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;There is increased interest in and potential benefits from using large language models (LLMs) in medicine. However, by simply wondering how the LLMs and the applications powered by them will reshape medicine instead of getting actively involved, the agency in shaping how these tools can be used in medicine is lost.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3&gt;Observations&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Applications powered by LLMs are increasingly used to perform medical tasks without the underlying language model being trained on medical records and without verifying their purported benefit in performing those tasks.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3&gt;Conclusions and Relevance&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;The creation and use of LLMs in medicine need to be actively shaped by provisioning relevant training data, specifying the desired benefits, and evaluating the benefits via testing in real-world deployments.&lt;/p&gt;" /><meta name="citation_journal_title" content="JAMA" /><meta name="citation_journal_abbrev" content="JAMA" /><meta name="citation_volume" content="330" /><meta name="citation_issue" content="9" /><meta name="citation_publication_date" content="2023/09/05" /><meta name="citation_issn" content="0098-7484" /><meta name="citation_publisher" content="American Medical Association" /><meta name="citation_reference" content="citation_title=How chatbots and large language model artificial intelligence systems will reshape modern medicine: fountain of creativity or Pandora’s box?; citation_author=Li  R; citation_author=Kumar  A; citation_author=Chen  JH;  citation_journal_title=JAMA Intern Med;  citation_year=2023;  citation_volume=183;  citation_issue=6;  citation_pages=596-597; " /><meta name="citation_reference" content="citation_author=Vaswani  A; citation_author=Shazeer  N; citation_author=Parmar  N; citation_publisher=Curran Associates Inc, ;  citation_title=Proceedings of the 31st International Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems: NIPS ’17;  citation_year=2017;  citation_pages=6000-6010; " /><meta name="citation_reference" content="citation_title=A survey of large language models.; citation_author=Zhao  WX; citation_author=Zhou  K; citation_author=Li  J;  citation_journal_title=arXiv; " /><meta name="citation_reference" content="citation_title=Benefits, limits, and risks of GPT-4 as an AI chatbot for medicine.; citation_author=Lee  P; citation_author=Bubeck  S; citation_author=Petro  J;  citation_journal_title=N Engl J Med;  citation_year=2023;  citation_volume=388;  citation_issue=13;  citation_pages=1233-1239; " /><meta name="citation_reference" content="Wikipedia contri